==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ruff
<hw>Ruff</hw> <pr>(r⟦ucr⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>ronfle</ets>; cf. It. <ets>ronfa</ets>, Pg. <ets>rufa</ets>,
<ets>rifa</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A
game similar to whist, and the predecessor of it.</def>
<rj><au>Nares.</au></rj> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The act of trumping,
especially when one has no card of the suit led.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ruff
<hw>Ruff</hw>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>To
trump.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ruff
<hw>Ruff</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Of uncertain origin: cf. Icel.
<ets>r⟦umac⟧finn</ets> rough, uncombed, Pr. <ets>ruf</ets> rude, rough,
Sp. <ets>rufo</ets> frizzed, crisp, curled, G. <ets>raufen</ets> to
pluck, fight, <ets>rupfen</ets> to pluck, pull, E. <ets>rough</ets>.
⟦root⟧18. Cf. <er>Ruffle</er> to wrinkle.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
muslin or linen collar plaited, crimped, or fluted, worn formerly by
both sexes, now only by women and children.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here to-morrow with his best <qex>ruff</qex> on.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His gravity is much lessened since the late proclamation came out
against <qex>ruffs</qex>; . . . they were come to that height of excess
herein, that twenty shillings were used to be paid for starching of a
<qex>ruff</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Howell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Something formed with plaits or flutings, like the
collar of this name.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I reared this flower; . . . ⟦br⟧
Soft on the paper <qex>ruff</qex> its leaves I spread.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An exhibition of pride or haughtiness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How many princes . . . in the <qex>ruff</qex> of all their glory,
have been taken down from the head of a conquering army to the wheel of
the victor's chariot!</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Wanton or tumultuous procedure or conduct.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To ruffle it out in a riotous <qex>ruff</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A low, vibrating beat of a drum,
not so loud as a roll; a ruffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>A collar on a shaft ot other
piece to prevent endwise motion. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of
<er>Collar</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A set of lengthened or otherwise
modified feathers round, or on, the neck of a bird.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A limicoline bird of
Europe and Asia (<spn>Pavoncella pugnax</spn>, syn. <spn>Philomachus
pugnax</spn>) allied to the sandpipers. The males during the breeding
season have a large ruff of erectile feathers, variable in their colors,
on the neck, and yellowish naked tubercles on the face. They are
polygamous, and are noted for their pugnacity in the breeding season.
The female is called <stype>reeve</stype>, or
<stype>rheeve</stype>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A variety of the domestic
pigeon, having a ruff of its neck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Ruff
<hw>Ruff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Ruffed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Ruffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To ruffle; to
disorder.</def> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To beat with the ruff or ruffle,
as a drum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Hawking)</fld> <def>To hit, as the prey, without
fixing it.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Card Playing)</fld> <def>To play a trump card at
bridge; <as>as, he <ex>ruffed</ex> his partner's ace</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ruffe</ent>⟦br⟧
